headline: Venezuela's Chavez Has Overcome Lung Infection
summary: Venezuela's cancer-stricken President Hugo Chavez has overcome a lung infection that he had faced after his latest surgery in Cuba 45 days ago.

headline: Venezuela Promises Investigation Into Prison Riot
summary: Venezuelan officials on Saturday promised an "ample" investigation into a prison riot in a northwestern state that has reportedly left more than 50 people dead and has renewed focus on the country's notoriously overcrowded and violent penitentiary system.

headline: Dozens Dead as Clashes Grip Egypt
summary: Dozens were killed in a second day of violence across Egypt, stoked in part by a court's declaration of death sentences in last year's soccer riot.

headline: Harkin's Exit Heralds Scramble for Senate Seat
summary: Iowa Democrat Tom Harkin's announcement that he won't seek re-election in 2014 heralds a wide-open race for his Senate seat.

headline: Friends Mourn Texan Killed in Algerian Attack
summary: Friends and co-workers at his funeral Saturday remembered Frederick Buttaccio, 58, a Texan who died this month in a terrorist attack on an Algerian natural-gas plant, as an outgoing and energetic man.

headline: French Forces Near Key City in Mali
summary: French forces took control of the airport and a key bridge in Gao, marking a significant inroad into territory held by al Qaeda-linked extremists.

headline: SNC-Lavalin Faces New Allegations in Probe
summary: SNC-Lavalin Group, the Montreal engineering firm at the center of several probes into allegedly improper overseas payments, said it was looking into fresh allegations contained in a police affidavit.

headline: Suicide Bombers Kill 12 in Afghanistan
summary: Suicide bombers targeting law-enforcement authorities killed at least 12 people in two separate incidents in Afghanistan on Saturday, underscoring the precarious security in the country as U.S.-led forces prepare to withdraw.

headline: Ex-Premier Zeman Elected Czech President
summary: Czech voters on Saturday chose Milos Zeman, a left-leaning former prime minister, to be their new president, setting the stage for a more pro-EU tone in national affairs.

headline: Deutsche Telekom Eyes Stake in Wi-Fi Operator
summary: Germany's largest telecommunications company, Deutsche Telekom, is considering a stake in Wi-Fi operator Fon to cope with exploding mobile data traffic.

headline: Azarenka Wins Australian Open
summary: Victoria Azarenka won her second straight Australian Open title on Saturday, beating China's Li Na in a final that included a break for fireworks and two medical timeouts.

headline: Photos of the Week: Jan. 20-26
summary: In this week's photos, a man looks at a sculpture in Singapore, a U.S. soldier bench-presses an Afghan soldier in Afghanistan, Russia's Maria Sharapova serves the ball during a quarterfinal match at the Australian Open, and more.

headline: India Republic Day Passes Peacefully
summary: Indians celebrated Republic Day on Saturday without major incident except in disputed Kashmir, where separatists held a general strike to protest Indian rule.

headline: Algeria Admits Mistakes in Standoff
summary: Algeria's foreign minister said security forces made mistakes in a hostage crisis at a gas plant in which many foreign workers were killed by Algerian military strikes.

headline: Canadians Missing in Antarctica Believed Dead
summary: Three Canadian men missing in Antarctica are believed dead after the wreckage of the plane they were traveling in was found, the New Zealand rescue service said Saturday.

headline: N.Y. Scraps Privatizing Parking Meters
summary: New York City is scrapping plans to privatize management of its street-parking system, the latest sign of growing wariness in U.S. cities of initiatives to address budget woes by selling off the rights to run meters and lots.

headline: Build an Extra-Fragrant Fire
summary: Naturally aromatic logs elevate the hearth to new scent heights.
